column1: #title: Tropospheric Ozone Assessment Report (TOAR) aggregated metrics file
#author: Schultz, MG, Forschungszentrum Juelich GmbH, Juelich, Germany (m.schultz@fz-juelich.de)
#citation: Schultz, MG et al. (2017): Tropospheric Ozone Assessment Report, Global surface ozone datasets. https://doi.org/10.1594/PANGAEA.876108
#project: Tropospheric Ozone Assessment Report (TOAR), an IGAC-sponsored activity
#data_source: Surface ozone database at Juelich Supercomputing Centre, Forschungszentrum Juelich, Germany
#data_source_description: The TOAR surface ozone database contains hourly surface ozone measurements from over 9,600 stations around the world made between 1970 and 2015.

#data_source_reference: Schultz, MG et al. (2017): Tropospheric Ozone Assessment Report: Database and Metrics Data of Global Surface Ozone Observations. Elementa - Science of the Anthropocene, http://doi.org/10.1525/elementa.244

#data_use_policy: If you make use of this dataset in your own presentations or publications, please do three things: 1. cite the dataset (see citation above),  2. cite the data_source_reference, 3. acknowledge the TOAR initiative (http://www.igacproject.org/activities/TOAR)
#dataset_description: This file contains several statistical quantities and ozone metrics from the TOAR database at individual stations with at least 3 years of data between 2010 and 2014
column2: data were aggregated as average summer values during this period

column1: #data_aggregation_period: summer months (April-September in Northern hemisphere, October-March in Southern hemisphere)

column2: name of the measurement network/data center from which the data originated
alphanumeric identifier of station according to network conventions
name of the station as provided by network data center or station PI
country operating the station (ISO names with few exceptions)
characterization of station as "traffic", "industry", or "background" according to data provider
classification of station environment as "urban", "suburban", "rural", or "remote" according to data provider
altitude of station above sea level (m)
altitude of station according to Google(c) maps
relative altitude of station versus minimum altitude in 5 km circle around station, based on ETOPO version 1 topography
population density at station according to GPW version 3 (people km-2)
maximum population density in 5 km radius around station location (people km-2)
maximum population density in 25 km radius around station location (people km-2)
stable nighttime light intensity index from NOAA-DMSP (index)
averaged nighttime light intensity index within 5 km radius around station (index)
maximum nighttime light intensity index within 25 km radius around station (index)
region code according to TFHTAP region mapping (integer)
numerical code designating climatic zone of station location according to IPCC, 2006
numeric code designating the dominant landcover type at station location from https://lpdaac.usgs.gov/dataset_discovery/modis/modis_products_table/mcd12c1
percent fractions of most important landcover type classes (text)
NOx emissions estimate (g m-2 yr-1) from http://edgar.jrc.ec.europa.eu/htap_v2/index.php?SECURE=123
tropospheric NO2 column density (10^15 molecules cm-2) from Ozone Monitoring Instrument
globally consistent, objective station classifier "urban", "rural, low elevation", "rural, high elevation", or "unclassified" based on thresholds of nightlight, population_density, and no2_column
fraction of hourly data values available in averaging period, averaged over 2010-2014
4th highest daily maximum 8-hour ozone mixing ratio (nmol mol-1), averaged over 2010-2014, relaxed data capture criterion, time window definition according to US EPA
as dma8epa, but with strict data capture criterion (matching the US EPA definition, but without the exception rules)
4th highest daily maximum 8-hour ozone mixing ratio (nmol mol-1), averaged over 2010-2014, relaxed data capture criterion, time window definition according to 2016 US EPA standard
as dma8epax, but with strict data capture criterion
as dma8epa, but 26th highest time window definition according to EU regulations, relaxed data capture threshold
as dma8eu, but with strict data capture criterion
average value of daily maximum 8-hour average ozone mixing ratios
sum of daily maximum 8-hour mean ozone mixing ratios exceeding 10 nmol mol-1, time window according to EU regulations, relaxed data capture criterion
as somo10, but with strict data capture threshold as defined in the EU regulations
sum of daily maximum 8-hour mean ozone mixing ratios exceeding 35 nmol mol-1, time window according to EU regulations, relaxed data capture criterion
as somo35, but with strict data capture threshold as defined in the EU regulations
4th highest daily maximum 5-hour W90 exposure index, averaged over 2010-2014
number of days with exceedance of dma8epax above 50 nmol mol-1, averaged over 2010-2014
number of days with exceedance of dma8epax above 60 nmol mol-1, averaged over 2010-2014
number of days with exceedance of dma8epax above 70 nmol mol-1, averaged over 2010-2014
number of days with exceedance of dma8epax above 80 nmol mol-1, averaged over 2010-2014
number of days with exceedance of daily maximum 1-hour ozone mixing ratios above 90 nmol mol-1, averaged over 2010-2014
number of days with exceedance of daily maximum 1-hour ozone mixing ratios above 100 nmol mol-1, averaged over 2010-2014
number of days with exceedance of daily maximum 1-hour ozone mixing ratios above 120 nmol mol-1, averaged over 2010-2014
median ozone mixing ratio, averaged over 2010-2014
cumulative daytime ozone mixing ratio above 40 nmol mol-1,, averaged over 2010-2014
as aot40, but using solar zenith angle to identify daytime instead of fixed 12-hour window
as daylight_aot40, but accumulating over dark periods
cumulative W126 exposure index derived from daytime ozone mixing ratios
as w126, but accumulated over 24 hours instead of 12 hours per day
mean annual average of daytime ozone mixing ratios, i.e. between 8 and 20 h local time (nmol mol-1)
mean annual average of nighttime ozone mixing ratios, i.e. between 20 and 8 h local time (nmol mol-1)
maximum of 3-months running mean of daily maximum 1-hour ozone mixing ratios (nmol mol-1)
day of the year when drmdmax1h occured, average over 3-5 year period
column3: warning: potentially flawed for southern hemisphere stations

column2: number of years included in the various metrics values
